{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17648623","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17648623"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:55:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:55:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18323"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18323","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18323"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0,0.4,0.07,0.43]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11041"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77617"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11041","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11041"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18323"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63130"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5112"},{"type":"tags","id":"11073"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25619"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25623"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77617","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77617"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old woman presents to the Oncology clinic with a history of breast cancer diagnosed two years ago. She has recently developed worsening bone pain over the past month. She has a medical history of hypertension and osteoporosis. Her current medications include lisinopril and calcium supplements. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Imaging studies reveal multiple lytic lesions in the spine and pelvis consistent with bone metastases.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following treatments may be used to manage her bone metastases?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Immunotherapy","Surgical resection","Bisphosphonates","Hormonal therapy","Chemotherapy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBisphosphonates\u003C/strong\u003E are commonly used to treat bone metastases by inhibiting osteoclast-mediated bone resorption, thereby reducing skeletal-related events such as fractures and pain. They are particularly effective in cancers that commonly metastasise to bone, such as breast cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChemotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E may be used to treat the primary cancer and any metastatic disease, but it is not specifically targeted at bone metastases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHormonal therapy\u003C/strong\u003E can be effective in hormone receptor-positive breast cancer, but it does not directly address bone metastases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmunotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E is a treatment option for certain types of cancer, but it is not specifically used for bone metastases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical resection\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered in cases of isolated bone metastases causing significant symptoms or complications, but it is not a primary treatment for widespread bone metastases.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Bisphosphonates are used to treat bone metastases by inhibiting osteoclast-mediated bone resorption.","Bone metastases can cause significant morbidity, including pain and fractures, and require targeted management.","Other treatments for bone metastases include denosumab, radiation therapy, and surgery."],"references":["Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2021). Textbook of Orthopaedics, 2e-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Mohan, H. (2018). Textbook of pathology. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers","Momodu II, Savaliya V. Osteomyelitis. [Updated 2023 May 31]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK532250/","Folpe, A., \u0026 Nielsen, G. P. (Eds.). (2022). Bone and Soft Tissue Pathology E-Book: A Volume in the Foundations in Diagnostic Pathology Series. Elsevier Health Sciences","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Ferguson, J. L., \u0026 Turner, S. P. (2018). Bone Cancer: Diagnosis and Treatment Principles. American family physician, 98(4), 205\u2013213"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63130"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18323"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63130","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63130"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T20:38:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-07T20:38:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11041"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77617"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"7